Kalila de Oliveira Bassanetti – 08/11/2024
Individual Technology Adoption Strategy Proposal
Wisconsin Maritime Museum
I. Introduction
This proposal aims to support users of the Wisconsin Maritime Museum in analyzing
the data available in its online collection. The museum’s main goal is to engage and educate
the public on topics related to the Great Lakes, Wisconsin’s maritime history, and ships. This
proposal focuses on the development of a tool that uses web scraping and geocoding
technologies in Python to create visualizations of the online collection metadata, including
maps with the location of photographs.
II. Institutional profile
The Wisconsin Maritime Museum is an institution located in Manitowoc, in the state
of Wisconsin, United States. It was created in 1969 – initially, its name was Manitowoc
Submarine Memorial Association. Focused on the maritime history of Wisconsin and the
Great Lakes, the museum attracts a significant number of visitors. As shown in their 2023
report, more than 30,000 people visited the museum
1
. The staff comprises 11 employees, not
including volunteers, and the board of trustees has 12 members.
The institution’s main activities are exhibits, field trips, and outreach events. Users
include students, researchers, and people interested in the subject. Even though each group of
users has specific data needs, this tool could be helpful for all of them. For example, it could
1

aid researchers to quickly grasp what is available given their needs, such as which places are
documented. It could also be useful for the general public to consume information in a more
visual way, without too many details that could be overwhelming.
The online collection has a fraction of the museum’s collection, with a strong
emphasis on photographs. Each photograph record has its own metadata. Not all fields are
complete in each of the items, but there is still a significant amount of information available.
Data types encountered in the online collection are strings for fields such as description,
search terms, object name, and people. The description field, specifically, can have much
information, which could lead to different types of analysis using text analysis, for instance.
The example of a photograph record below has information that could be used in research
about safety committees. Search terms, object name, and people have more concise texts, as
seen in the example below.
Example of photograph record
The field date is usually in the MM/DD/YYYY format, although sometimes it has
only a year, or an approximate date, written as a string. Similarly, the field accession
generally denotes the accession date, but sometimes it can be an id in a string format.
The development of a tool that could process this data is important for the users, but it
would also require skilled employees to create it. There is a need to work with texts,
incomplete dates, and fields with different data types, for example.
III. Technology Overview
In order to understand the information regarding the museum’s online collection of
photographs, there is a need to access all of the metadata fields and be able to sort the ones
we are interested in. Web scraping is a great tool to accomplish this, as it allows us to extract
data from websites.
This proposal’s tool aims to gather the photographs’ metadata and parse location data
to create maps. It would help researchers to see the geographic information from a new
perspective, and it could possibly bring some new questions that would not come up through
the visualization of one photograph at a time, such as “What are the most documented areas
in the museum’s photograph collection?”. This would help to fulfill one of the declared
purposes of the museum, which is to “create personal and meaningful connections with our
waterways”
2
. It is interesting to analyze the big picture of the collection, and to understand its
strengths and weaknesses – the lack of information is also information.
IV. Issues of power / Power mitigation
This tool can be used to understand the strengths of the collection, such as the items,
periods, persons, or places that are more documented. It can also be used to understand the
weaknesses of the collection, or what information is missing. A potential bias resulting from
this tool is that, since some of the items lack specific metadata fields, it would not be an
accurate portrait of the collection. If this technology is used for the purposes of analyzing the
people in the photographs, for instance, it would also result in biased information, as there are
photographs where they are not identified.
2
https://www.wisconsinmaritime.org/about-us/
One feature of the technology in this proposal is that it allows us to measure bias in
the collection. We can have an overall understanding of the historical periods represented, the
ports in Wisconsin (and other regions, especially around the Great Lakes), the people and
companies involved in the maritime industry, and so on. Having this information also leads to
the acknowledgement of the information that is missing in the collections, which could
prompt the staff to try to acquire documents from places, periods or people that are
underrepresented.
While the tool developed for this proposal focuses on the geographic component,
there is other information that could also be summarized using text and data analysis. For
example, some of the long descriptions for each photograph could be analyzed to identify
important topics of the period being represented. Another example would be regarding the
people represented in the photographs. We see many indications of “sponsors”, but there are
other professions/descriptions that could be in the photographs, such as those related to crew
members. It would be interesting to analyze this feature more systematically from the
information available in the metadata.
One way to address issues of lack of information would be to have well documented
datasheets for the datasets. An adaptation of the model presented by Gebru, Timnit et al.
(2021) would be a good solution, with emphasis on what is missing and why. It is interesting
to add that a significant part of the collection was donated to the museum, which explains the
lack of more information. Nevertheless, having a datasheet with all the details available
regarding the collection process could help explain the gaps in the visualizations, and give
more context.
The Date field can also result in biased information, as the dates mentioned are not
standardized (some variations are the year, the full date, “circa”, etc.). This tool could be
adjusted to focus only on years, for instance, or decades.
V. The Code
The initial part of the code is web scraping. For this proposal, the first 20 results of the
photograph section in the online collection were used.
Image 1
BeautifulSoup is used to extract specific HTML data. In this case, we need to extract
the URLs of the photographs displayed.
Image 2
The URLs, then, are displayed in a list.
Image 3
With the URLs, it is possible to extract the metadata from each photograph.
Image 4
To make it possible to gather the data from the Place field, it helps to have it as
column.
Image 5
The next step is to identify the unique places that appear in the list.
Image 6
Finally, we enter the places on a map.
Image 7
The maps can show which places are more represented than others and trigger the
staff to actively search for items related to underrepresented ports.
This proposal could be extended to other metadata fields, such as date. It would be
possible to analyze the historical periods that are represented, and when those photographs
joined the museum’s collection. Another interesting field to be analyzed in such a way is
“people”, which would allow users to analyze the representativeness of women, for example.
Depending on the data, text analysis is also an option to identify professions associated with
the persons, which might reveal whether crew or sponsors are relatively more represented in
the collection.
